# three-js Best Practices

This guide defines definitive standards for building robust, performant, and maintainable three.js applications using modern JavaScript and WebGL optimization techniques.

These rules are based on three.js official documentation and community performance guidelines.

---

## 1. Resource Management & Disposal

WebGL resources are **not automatically freed by the browser**. Explicit disposal is required to avoid GPU memory leaks.

### ✅ GOOD: Explicit Disposal of GPU Resources

Always call `.dispose()` on:

- `BufferGeometry`
- `Material`
- `Texture`
- `WebGLRenderTarget`

```javascript
geometry.dispose();
material.dispose();
texture.dispose();
renderTarget.dispose();
````

This prevents memory leaks even after removing objects from the scene. ([Three.js][1])

### ❌ BAD: Relying on Garbage Collection

```javascript
scene.remove(mesh);
// mesh and its resources still occupy GPU memory!
mesh = null; // Does NOT free GPU resources
```

---

## 2. Asset Loading & Lazy Fetching

three.js provides async loaders that **do not block the main thread** and report progress.

### ✅ GOOD: Async Asset Loaders

Use official loaders like `GLTFLoader`, `TextureLoader`, etc., to load assets asynchronously:

```javascript
import { GLTFLoader } from 'three/addons/loaders/GLTFLoader.js';
await loader.loadAsync('model.glb'); // non‑blocking asset loading
```

Three.js loaders handle progressive loading and errors internally. ([Three.js][2])

### ❌ BAD: Blocking or Premature Loading

Loading everything at once at startup without showing progress leads to UI stalls.

```javascript
// Bad UX: loading all assets synchronously at init
const texture = new THREE.TextureLoader().load('huge.jpg'); 
```

---

## 3. Render Performance Optimization

Most performance problems come from **draw calls, shader cost, and texture memory pressure**. ([threejsdemos.com][3])

### ✅ GOOD: Reduce Draw Calls

Minimize the number of unique geometry/material combinations.

* Use `InstancedMesh` to render many copies of the same mesh with one draw call.
* Merge static geometry where possible.

```javascript
const instanced = new THREE.InstancedMesh(geometry, material, count);
scene.add(instanced);
```

Instancing dramatically reduces GPU overhead. ([threejsdemos.com][3])

### ✅ GOOD: Reuse Materials & Geometries

Avoid creating new material/geometry for each object if they are identical.

```javascript
const sharedMaterial = new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial();
```

---

## 4. Profiling & Diagnostics

Use renderer and browser tools to discover performance bottlenecks.

### ✅ GOOD: Using `renderer.info`

Inspect draw calls and memory:

```javascript
console.log(renderer.info);
```

This helps identify whether new resources are being created each frame. ([Three.js][1])

### ✅ GOOD: Browser DevTools Profiling

Use Chrome/Firefox performance and memory profilers to pinpoint:

* CPU vs GPU time
* Garbage collection spikes
* Memory leaks

---

## 5. Scene Update Efficiency

### ✅ GOOD: Avoid Allocations in Loop

Allocate objects outside the render loop to reduce GC pressure.

```javascript
// Bad: new Vector3() inside loop
for (…) {
  const v = new THREE.Vector3();
}
```

Reuse temporary vectors instead:

```javascript
const tmp = new THREE.Vector3();
```

---

## 6. Model & Texture Optimization

### ✅ GOOD: Pre‑Optimize Models

Reduce polygon count and compress models before shipping. High‑res models with millions of polygons may never achieve 60 FPS. ([MeshOpt API][4])

### ✅ GOOD: Use Texture Compression

Compressed textures reduce memory and bandwidth.

---

## 7. Practical Load & Display Patterns

### ✅ GOOD: Show Loading Progress

Use `onProgress` callback from loaders to display progress UI.

```javascript
loader.load(url, onLoad, onProgress, onError);
```

This improves perceived performance.

---

## 8. WebGL Error Handling

three.js does not provide high‑level wrappers for WebGL errors. Use profiling tools instead of frequent runtime calls like `gl.getError()` — these are low‑level WebGL diagnostics not commonly used in three.js production patterns.

Use **`renderer.info` and browser profiler tools** to inspect rendering stats. ([Three.js][1])

---

## 9. Project Workflow & Tooling

### ✅ GOOD: Modular Three.js with npm & ES Modules

Use npm and import modules from “three/addons” for loader and helper code.

```javascript
import * as THREE from 'three';
import { GLTFLoader } from 'three/addons/loaders/GLTFLoader.js';
```

This keeps code modern and tree‑shakable.

---

## 10. Render Loop Best Practices

### ✅ GOOD: requestAnimationFrame Loop

Use `requestAnimationFrame()` for render loops. Avoid unnecessary renders if no state change.

### ❌ BAD: Constant Full Renders

Always rendering every frame even when static leads to wasted CPU/GPU cycles.

---

## Golden Rules

* Explicitly dispose all GPU resources. ([Three.js][1])
* Reduce draw calls with instancing and geometry merging. ([threejsdemos.com][3])
* Reuse materials and geometries. ([threejsdemos.com][3])
* Profile with `renderer.info` + browser tools. ([Three.js][1])
* Load assets asynchronously with official loaders. ([Three.js][2])
* Pre‑optimize models and textures for best runtime performance. ([MeshOpt API][4])


